  "prompt": "Why does God create people who he knows will end up in hell?",
  "response": "That's a complex theological question that different religious traditions answer differently. Some perspectives include:\n\n1. Free will argument:\n- God gives humans free choice to accept or reject Him\n- People choose their own spiritual destiny\n- God doesn't predestine people to hell\n\n2. Divine purpose perspective:\n- God's ways are ultimately mysterious\n- Human understanding is limited\n- His plan includes allowing individual choices\n\n3. Calvinist view:\n- God's sovereignty means He ultimately determines salvation\n- Some are chosen for salvation, others for judgment\n\n4. Love and relationship perspective:\n- God desires genuine relationship, not forced worship\n- Free choice allows authentic love\n\n5. Redemptive view:\n- God's ultimate goal is redemption and restoration\n- Even potential rejection doesn't negate His love\n\nThese are simplified explanations of deep theological debates. Different Christian denominations and theologians offer nuanced interpretations.\n\nUltimately, this question touches on profound theological mysteries about God's nature, human free will, and divine justice.\n\nWould you be interested in exploring any of these perspectives more deeply?",
